<br>
1.  Hands down final fantasy VII.  I replayed that game so many times, I knew pretty much every little corner of the game.  Death of aeris = first time in a game where you get an emotional shock.  CG cinema's really help with those poignant moments such as her death.  The weapons are to this day my favorite optional bosses, just because they were truly a challenge.  <br>
<br>
2.  Xenogears.  This game rules, nothing else need be said.<br>
<br>
3.  I think it was final fantasy IV, not sure, the one with cecil the dark knight.  I got hooked on finding all the hidden items in that game, i actually kept it 20 days late from a library back when I was like 13.  I kept tryin to get that elusive pink puff tail, never did though.  Plus, its still a game I have np playing today.<br>
<br>
4.  I dont know how many of you are familiar with this game, though maybe somebody is, I didnt read this whole thread, so have no clue.  The game was for the Sega Saturn, called Dragon Force.  It is a highly addictive game, where you have generals who face off against enemy generals one on one on a 3d field of battle.  That may not seem like much, but the generals can have up to 100 soldiers each, and each soldier is there for you to see, and even count.  Each general sends all their soldiers at each other, and you can give general commands, and then watch them go.  The final boss in that game rules to.<br>
<br>
5.  Last, but not least, I would have to rank the Lunar games here, both part one and two.  They have humor, funny anime cinema's, and are just fun.  I own both versions of both Lunar's, the ones on the sega cd, and the ones on the playstation.  If I ever get my sega cd fixxed, I think I would enjoy the originals more than the playstation version, but the playstation versions are still as good as they come. <p><br>
